## Debounce Function

```javascript
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}
```

**Usage:**

```javascript
const handleSearch = debounce((query) => {
  fetch(`/api/search?q=${query}`);
}, 300);

input.addEventListener("input", (e) => handleSearch(e.target.value));
```

---

## How it works

Every time the debounced function is called, it cancels the previous pending timer and starts a new one. The wrapped function only executes after the delay has elapsed **without another call arriving**. If calls keep coming in faster than the delay, the function never fires until they stop.

---

## When to use it

| Scenario | Why |
|---|---|
| Search input | Avoid an API call on every keystroke; wait until the user pauses |
| Window resize handler | Recalculating layouts is expensive; only do it once resizing stops |
| Form auto-save | Don't write to the server on every character change |
| Button click guard | Prevent accidental double-submits |

**Rule of thumb:** use debounce when you care about the *final* value after a burst of events, not the intermediate ones. If you need the *first* event and want to ignore the rest, use **throttle** instead.
